</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="77797F1F573058449F20D567E18BFBCA" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="B196E61261957C3C046E48BC75D9E6ED" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F828CBA66F93882FDA50CF564C102681" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">
The lone specimen representing this species is labelled as 
<normalizedToken id="98BD6BADFBDCA79A44B5790957980ECA" originalValue="Perkins’">Perkins'</normalizedToken>
lot 170, Kaunakakai, July 1893, sea level. 
<normalizedToken id="A7745F855E87FF7071C643B0B693C994" originalValue="Perkins’">Perkins'</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken id="682E6B5AC43DD70F17F4C90E67C5B107" originalValue="Moloka‘i">Moloka'i</normalizedToken>
July collecting commenced on 9 July, however much of his time was spent high in the forests (
<bibRefCitation id="C13A6C5041D2E843E5076462D9C65E53" author="Evenhuis, NL" journalOrPublisher="Bishop Museum Press, Honolulu" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" refId="B39" refString="Evenhuis, NL, 2007. Barefoot on Lava: The Journals and Correspondence of Naturalist R.C.L. Perkins in Hawai'i, 1892-1901. Bishop Museum Press, Honolulu" title="Barefoot on Lava: The Journals and Correspondence of Naturalist R. C. L. Perkins in Hawai'i, 1892 - 1901." year="2007">Evenhuis 2007</bibRefCitation>
). He walked to the coast on 17 July, arriving at Kaunakakai in the afternoon. He spent the next two days hunting shorebirds and coots, and on the 20th &quot;Walked along the coast to Kaluaaha supposed to be about 16 miles E. ... I stayed some time at Kawela ... (
<bibRefCitation id="C2961729DF5754A5DB0691638BD2208C" author="Evenhuis, NL" journalOrPublisher="Bishop Museum Press, Honolulu" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" refId="B39" refString="Evenhuis, NL, 2007. Barefoot on Lava: The Journals and Correspondence of Naturalist R.C.L. Perkins in Hawai'i, 1892-1901. Bishop Museum Press, Honolulu" title="Barefoot on Lava: The Journals and Correspondence of Naturalist R. C. L. Perkins in Hawai'i, 1892 - 1901." year="2007">Evenhuis 2007</bibRefCitation>
: 262).&quot; After his midday stop at the base of Kawela Gulch he encountered a &quot;heavy shower&quot; and &quot;finishing of the school term&quot; at Kalua 'aha. The next day he walked back to Kaunakakai, and on the 21st came down with a sore throat, which progressed to what he self-diagnosed as &quot;the 
<normalizedToken id="2871841D58503507DDB3C9AA6C7E63E5" originalValue="‘grippe’">'grippe'</normalizedToken>
or influenza (
<bibRefCitation id="CAF6A1EAE2E4B6368AB3426BB2F8DB4F" author="Evenhuis, NL" journalOrPublisher="Bishop Museum Press, Honolulu" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" refId="B39" refString="Evenhuis, NL, 2007. Barefoot on Lava: The Journals and Correspondence of Naturalist R.C.L. Perkins in Hawai'i, 1892-1901. Bishop Museum Press, Honolulu" title="Barefoot on Lava: The Journals and Correspondence of Naturalist R. C. L. Perkins in Hawai'i, 1892 - 1901." year="2007">Evenhuis 2007</bibRefCitation>
: 163).&quot; He returned to the mountains on 24 July, closing the temporal window during which 
<taxonomicName id="4668E54A12F56F1AD59BC774A9670485" genus="P." lsidName="P. perkinsi" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" rank="species" species="perkinsi">
<emphasis id="19A2C71A8D36069D763734590A518B76" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">P. perkinsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could have been collected. Thus, a best guess concerning the collecting locality of the lone 
<taxonomicName id="C7203110107E9D3E74E339A100118AAD" authority="Casey, 1918" authorityName="Liebherr" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Paratachys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Paratachys perkinsi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perkinsi">
<emphasis id="FC27EFC646CFE177F82D274C2BEFBBDA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">Paratachys perkinsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is in the streambed of Kawela Gulch near the coast on 20 July (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="59FF500D400B3F827BCB901E983089CC" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Distributional records for Paratachys spp.; P. perkinsi (type locality designated as Kawela Gulch at sea level (•) (see text); P. haleakalae (▪)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1044.59674.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/553683" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">7</figureCitation>
). Such a situation would be similar to the streamside situations frequented by 
<taxonomicName id="5240F398725525A9C48DEC21EAAF3F7B" genus="P." lsidName="P. terryli" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" rank="species" species="terryli">
<emphasis id="B49B08BBAAD01BD24767A9E27A60DFCF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">P. terryli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of Kauai, although at considerably lower elevation. Kawela Stream at higher elevations houses several flightless riparian species, including the nabid bug, 
<taxonomicName id="EA2B5304F91EFD1C927AE70FB903C0A2" authorityName="Polhemus" authorityYear="1999" class="Insecta" family="Nabidae" genus="Nabis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nabis gagneorum" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gagneorum">
<emphasis id="04E35C0489B6DBA616499C6C7CC92D9C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">Nabis gagneorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<bibRefCitation id="2A18E4628A756EDBD8AC9573C0D1E2BA" author="Polhemus, DA" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" pagination="868 - 874" refId="B80" refString="Polhemus, DA, 1999. A new species of riparian Nabidae from the Hawaiian Islands. Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington 101: 868 - 874" title="A new species of riparian Nabidae from the Hawaiian Islands." volume="101" year="1999">Polhemus (1999)</bibRefCitation>
, and the very large-bodied, vestigially winged carabid beetle, 
<taxonomicName id="8E4489D8A4BE1B4F2D6FD80FFE7560A4" authorityName="Liebherr" authorityYear="2000" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Blackburnia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Blackburnia polhemusi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="polhemusi">
<emphasis id="3FF66572C9402A91EBE089B023C2EE2A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">Blackburnia polhemusi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Liebherr (
<bibRefCitation id="85F7C3CF86F7ED0AEB565B92F3879460" author="Liebherr, JK" journalOrPublisher="Atti Museo Regionale di Scienze Naturali" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" refId="B63" refString="Liebherr, JK, Zimmerman, EC, 2000. Hawaiian Carabidae (Coleoptera), part 1: introduction and tribe Platynini. Insects of Hawai'i 16. Honolulu, University of Hawai'i Press, [v +] 494 pp." title="Hawaiian Carabidae (Coleoptera), part 1: introduction and tribe Platynini. Insects of Hawai'i 16. Honolulu, University of Hawai'i Press, [v +] 494 pp." year="2000">Liebherr and Zimmerman 2000</bibRefCitation>
). The riparian habits of both of these species are unusual among their respective radiations, pointing to Kawela Gulch as a persistent and stable water source able to support populations of flightless insects.
</paragraph>
